PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Substantial funding is provided to the healthcare systems of low-income countries. However, an important challenge is to ensure that this funding is used efficiently. This challenge is complicated by the fact that a large share of healthcare services in low-income countries is provided by nonprofit health centers that often lack (i) effective governance structures and (ii) organizational know-how and adequate training. In this paper, we argue that the bundling of performance-based incentives with auditing and feedback (A health centers that only receive funding increase their scale but do not show improvements in operating efficiency or health outcomes.This paper was accepted by Lamar Pierce, organizations.Funding: This research was supported by the Agence Nationale de la Recherche [Grant Investissements d?Avenir (LabEx Ecodec)].Supplemental Material: The data files and online appendix are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2023.4846.
